post_text: This is John Embry, Technology Coordinator for the district. I want to apologize that the board meeting was not live broadcast as we had originally planned. We have never done a live broadcast before, but that is no excuse. From many of my Facebook users and from Facebook instructions, I was informed that all I would have to do was push the live button and it would broadcast. That was not the case. I will investigate as to why, so that in the future, we can provide this to you. I thank those in the audience that posted the meeting through their personal pages.

post_text:
Congratulations to the first of the FBLA State Leadership Conference top 10 placers and National qualifiers! Alyxandra Eidson and Cece Forrest placed 6th in Insurance and Risk Management and Introduction to Business Communication, respectively. Three students placed in the top 4, qualifying to compete at the virtual National Leadership Experience this summer. Joseph Colston placed 4th in Computer Problem Solving, and is Dee-Mack FBLA's first member to qualify for Nationals three times. Tessa Howard placed 3rd in Business Law, and Allison Vogel placed 1st in Business Communication, earning a $75 cash prize!

The next winners will be announced after the second virtual general session Tuesday evening.

While we are disappointed that we could not meet in Springfield and will not get to travel to Salt Lake City this summer, that does not change the fact that students studied on their own time to compete. Please congratulate all FBLA members who competed at State.

Dee-Mack Drive-In Graduation Ceremony Detailsüë®‚Äçüéìüë©‚Äçüéì

5th Street between East and Kerlin will be closed Friday, May 15th from 6:30- 8:30 for our drive-in graduation ceremony (@7:00). (rain date is Saturday, May 16th) We are not allowed to have any spectators except the graduates and those living in their immediate homes attend. Therefore, we are broadcasting live through WJBC radio and streaming through NFHS. We want to make this ceremony as close to a traditional ceremony as possible within the guidelines and limitations. Thank you to Garden Gate Floral for helping us make this ‚Äúspecial‚Äù. Graduates only will be allowed out of their cars to walk a red carpet to the stage to get their diploma. A photographer will take their picture. We will have the traditional speeches and announcements of graduates, generations, local scholarships, etc. Graduates will arrive in decorated cars and will then proceed to a parade of graduates through town led by police, rescue, and fire! This class has already made history, let‚Äôs let them know how proud we are of their accomplishments!!!

In order to limit exposure for staff and families and so families don't have to drive out every day, here is a new procedure for lunches on March 30- April 3

and beyond. Lunches will be handed out on MONDAY, WEDNESDAY, and FRIDAY FROM 11:00-12:00 PM. (same locations)

Lunches on Monday will have two lunches for Monday and Tuesday.

Lunches on Wednesday will have two lunches for Wednesday and Thursday.

Lunch on Friday will have one lunch and snack.

Thank you so much to all our volunteers!

Please let me know if you know of any family that is not getting meals or needs food- we have resources to help.

We are all in this together!!!

post_text: This week was supposed to be the spring FBLA food drive for the Mackinaw Community Center Food Pantry, which desperately needs more food! We completely understand why there are limits on items, but if you are a Costco or Sam's shopper, or you can get a couple of extra items at the grocery store, please help FBLA support the work being done in Mackinaw to help those in need. Mrs. Desmond, FBLA sponsor, dropped off 5 boxes of items she collected from her neighborhood, much of it from people she has never met. In the words of Mother Theresa, "If you can't feed 100 people, then just feed one." ‚ù§ Thank you! Your support is appreciated! You can check the community center Facebook page for the next drop off day and time.

As we enter this unprecedented situation, a pressing concern the high school yearbook finds itself in is a lack of raw materials to create our pages. Losing a couple of weeks and some events will leave us scrambling for pictures to make the yearbook as good as it can be!

We are asking YOU to PLEASE send any pictures of anything fun/interesting/cool that any Dee-Mack High School students have done over the course of the school year, whether that is a sporting event, an in-school event, or just goofing off with friends outside of the classroom.

(We will of course give you a photo credit in the caption of the picture)

You would really be doing a fine service to your school and community! Thank you!

You can send them to jmclemor@deemack.org

post_text:
EARLY CHILDHOOD SCREENINGS



WHO: Children ages 0-5 living in Deer Creek-Mackinaw District #701

WHAT: Developmental Screenings

WHEN: Tuesday, March 24, 2020

WHERE: Deer Creek-Mackinaw Primary/Jr. High

PURPOSE: Screen developmental levels in motor skills, cognition, self-help & socialization skills, and speech & language.

For 3 & 4 year olds, this screening will determine if the child is eligible for our preschool program for next school year. Please note that the child must be three by June 1, 2020 to come to this screening. (Another screening will be held in August 2020 for children turning three before September 1).

To schedule a screening appointment, call Ann Schwarting @ (309) 359-5480 or email at aschwart@deemack.org

post_text:
The high school Future Business Leaders of America is currently selling ShowMe Dough products which include Butter Braids, pizza two-packs, and frozen cookie dough. All proceeds help pay for FBLA members' registration fees and hotel costs for the competitive events conferences. Last year, five Dee-Mack FBLA members qualified at the State Leadership Conference to compete at the National Leadership Conference, with two of those members placing in the top 10 in the nation in their event. FBLA gives our students wonderful opportunities for area, state and national recognition!

Please contact any FBLA member if you would like to order. You may email Mrs. Desmond at tdesmond@deemack.org for a list of FBLA members' names. Orders will be delivered to the high school on Nov. 1 in plenty of time for your holidays! Unfortunately, we can only accept local orders since students deliver the products. Thank you! We appreciate your support!

Tazewell County underage alcohol campaign:
‚ÄúHomecoming is an event that many look forward to, and one that often involves alcohol and underage drinking. Homecoming weekend can come with more chances and pressures for teens to drink. As a result, that often means more teens getting behind the wheel after they‚Äôve consumed alcohol. Teen drinking and alcohol-related crashes increase during the homecoming season. Car crashes are the number one cause of teen deaths, and of those fatal crashes, 30% involved underage drinking. The sad truth is that many teens across our country don‚Äôt come home after homecoming, because they were drinking or another driver did. Every teen has a reason not to drink. What‚Äôs your reason?‚Äù

post_text: High school FCCLA members are selling Beef House rolls, strawberry jam, and apple butter for the Thanksgiving and holiday seasons. Each package of rolls includes a dozen frozen yeast rolls and is $8. The jam and the apple butter are also $8 each. If you have never been to the Beef House, or had their rolls, you don't have to miss out any longer. Please consider purchasing from a FCCLA member for all of your holiday meals. Alternatively, you may email Ms. Webb at kwebb@deemack.org to place an order. Delivery will be on November 14, just in time for Thanksgiving.
